(lp3
VThe great texts of the ancient world
p4
aVdon't survive to us in their original form.
p5
aVThey survive because medieval scribes copied them
p6
aVand copied them and copied them.
p7
aVAnd so it is with Archimedes,
p8
aVthe great Greek mathematician.
p9
aa(lp10
VEverything we know about Archimedes as a mathematician
p11
aVwe know about because of just three books,
p12
aVand they're called A, B and C.
p13
aVAnd A was lost by an Italian humanist in 1564.
p14
aVAnd B was last heard of in the Pope's Library
p15
aVabout a hundred miles north of Rome in Viterbo in 1311.
p16
aVNow Codex C was only discovered in 1906,
p17
aVand it landed on my desk in Baltimore
p18
aVon the 19th of January, 1999.
p19
aVAnd this is Codex C here.
p20
aa(lp21
VNow Codex C is actually buried in this book.
p22
aVIt's buried treasure.
p23
aVBecause this book is actually a prayer book.
p24
aVIt was finished by a guy called Johannes Myrones
p25
aVon the 14th of April, 1229.
p26
aVAnd to make his prayer book he used parchment.
p27
aVBut he didn't use new parchment,
p28
aVhe used parchment recycled from earlier manuscripts,
p29
aVand there were seven of them.
p30
aVAnd Archimedes Codex C was just one of those seven.
p31
aVHe took apart the Archimedes manuscript and the other seven manuscripts.
p32
aVHe erased all of their texts,
p33
aVand then he cut the sheets down in the middle,
p34
aVhe shuffled them up,
p35
aVand he rotated them 90 degrees,
p36
aVand he wrote prayers on top of these books.
p37
aVAnd essentially these seven manuscripts
p38
aVdisappeared for 700 years, and we have a prayer book.
p39
aa(lp40
VThe prayer book was discovered by this guy,
p41
aVJohan Ludvig Heiberg, in 1906.
p42
aVAnd with just a magnifying glass,
p43
aVhe transcribed as much of the text as he could.
p44
aVAnd the thing is that he found two texts in this manuscript
p45
aVthat were unique texts.
p46
aVThey weren't in A and B at all;
p47
aVthey were completely new texts by Archimedes,
p48
aVand they were called "The Method" and "The Stomachion."
p49
aVAnd it became a world famous manuscript.
p50
aa(lp51
VNow it should be clear by now
p52
aVthat this book is in bad condition.
p53
aVIt got in worse condition in the 20th century
p54
aVafter Heiberg saw it.
p55
aVForgeries were painted over it,
p56
aVand it suffered very badly from mold.
p57
aVThis book is the definition of a write-off.
p58
aVIt's the sort of book
p59
aVthat you thought would be in an institution.
p60
aVBut it's not in an institution,
p61
aVit was bought by a private owner in 1998.
p62
aa(lp63
VWhy did he buy this book?
p64
aVBecause he wanted to make that which was fragile safe.
p65
aVHe wanted to make that which was unique ubiquitous.
p66
aVHe wanted to make that which was expensive free.
p67
aVAnd he wanted to do this as a matter of principle.
p68
aVBecause not many people are really going to read Archimedes in ancient Greek,
p69
aVbut they should have the chance to do it.
p70
aa(lp71
VSo he gathered around himself the friends of Archimedes,
p72
aVand he promised to pay for all the work.
p73
aVAnd it was an expensive job,
p74
aVbut actually it wouldn't be as much as you think
p75
aVbecause these people, they didn't come from money,
p76
aVthey came from Archimedes.
p77
aVAnd they came from all sorts of different backgrounds.
p78
aVThey came from particle physics,
p79
aVthey came from classical philology,
p80
aVthey came from book conservation,
p81
aVthey came from ancient mathematics,
p82
aVthey came from data management,
p83
aVthey came from scientific imaging and program management.
p84
aVAnd they got together to work on this manuscript.
p85
aa(lp86
VThe first problem was a conservation problem.
p87
aVAnd this is the sort of thing that we had to deal with:
p88
aVThere was glue on the spine of the book.
p89
aVAnd if you look at this photograph carefully,
p90
aVthe bottom half of this is rather brown.
p91
aVAnd that glue is hide glue.
p92
aVNow if you're a conservator,
p93
aVyou can take off this glue reasonably easily.
p94
aVThe top half is Elmer's wood glue.
p95
aVIt's polyvinyl acetate emulsion
p96
aVthat doesn't dissolve in water once it's dry.
p97
aVAnd it's much tougher than the parchment that it was written on.
p98
aVAnd so before we could start imaging Archimedes,
p99
aVwe had to take this book apart.
p100
aVSo it took four years to take apart.
p101
aVAnd this is a rare action shot, ladies and gentlemen.
p102
aa(lp103
V(Laughter)
